1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,080
Before we explore different types of iterations in this section,

2

00:00:04,080  -->  00:00:06,760
it's important to first think about and

3

00:00:06,760  -->  00:00:10,060
understand the role of the pass function in Python.

4

00:00:10,060  -->  00:00:13,820
Pass is a unique statement that essentially does nothing.

5

00:00:13,820  -->  00:00:17,060
Think of it like a box of error that occupies space.

6

00:00:17,060  -->  00:00:20,880
That being said, it's a powerful tool when you're writing Python code.

7

00:00:20,880  -->  00:00:23,480
It serves as a placeholder allowing you to

8

00:00:23,480  -->  00:00:26,380
define blocks of code that you plan to implement later on.

9

00:00:26,380  -->  00:00:28,340
By using pass, you can avoid

10

00:00:28,340  -->  00:00:32,180
syntax errors that occur when Python expects a block of code,

11

00:00:32,180  -->  00:00:35,015
but you're not ready to write it just yet.

12

00:00:35,015  -->  00:00:41,830
Frequently, pass is used in loops, functions, classes,

13

00:00:41,830  -->  00:00:45,690
and conditional statements, when you want to outline the structure of

14

00:00:45,690  -->  00:00:49,890
your code without filling in all of the details immediately.

15

00:00:49,890  -->  00:00:53,250
This is especially useful in incremental development,

16

00:00:53,250  -->  00:00:55,530
where you may want to keep certain parts of

17

00:00:55,530  -->  00:00:58,790
your code empty while you work on other sections.

18

00:00:58,790  -->  00:01:01,090
In summary, Pass is a simple,

19

00:01:01,090  -->  00:01:03,630
yet effective way to maintain the flow of your code

20

00:01:03,630  -->  00:01:07,630
and prevent errors as you build out your functions and scripts.
